./audit/12-accessibility-audit.md:4:This document audits accessibility risks across keyboard use, semantics, focus behavior, copy, contrast, and dense proof/admin surfaces.
./audit/12-accessibility-audit.md:9:- Proof surfaces use many `data-proof-*` hooks, which is good for testing structure but does not by itself ensure semantic accessibility.
./audit/12-accessibility-audit.md:25:  - explicit `tablist` / `tab` / `aria-selected` semantics on the major proof tab rails in `student-shell.tsx`, `risk-explorer.tsx`, `hod-pages.tsx`, and the system-admin detail rails
./audit/12-accessibility-audit.md:31:  - the remaining semantics gaps are now narrow enough to be covered by direct tests such as `tests/system-admin-accessibility-contracts.test.tsx` and `tests/ui-primitives-modal.test.tsx`
./audit/12-accessibility-audit.md:45:- Some controls use explicit button semantics, and acceptance scripts rely on role queries in many places, indicating the markup is not entirely div-driven.
./audit/12-accessibility-audit.md:46:- The major proof tab rails now expose explicit tab semantics instead of acting purely as visual segmented buttons.
./audit/12-accessibility-audit.md:50:- Keyboard-flow testing, live axe/browser checks, live accessibility-tree assertions, a generated screen-reader preflight transcript, and direct contract tests for tab semantics and modal focus behavior now exist for high-risk portal, admin, proof, dialog, and teacher proof paths, but the final human screen-reader pass is still absent.
./audit/12-accessibility-audit.md:51:- Dense custom UIs and inline-style-heavy implementations increase the chance of inconsistent focus rings, insufficient semantics, and unclear interactive affordances.
./audit/12-accessibility-audit.md:52:- The app’s information density raises cognitive accessibility concerns even where technical semantics may exist.
